Wash and dry all produce. Preheat #toaster oven{} or oven to 400 degrees. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @red onion{1}. Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a large pan over medium heat. Add onion and @sugar{1%tsp}. Cook, tossing, until browned, ~{6-8%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Remove from pan and set aside.

While onion cooks, mince or grate @garlic{1%clove} until you have ½ tsp (you may have a clove left over). In a #large bowl{}, whisk together @tomato paste{1/2%tbsp}, @balsamic vinegar{1%tbsp}, @olive oil{1%tbsp}, and as much minced garlic as you like (we sent more tomato paste and vinegar than needed). Season with salt and pepper.

Wipe out pan used for onion. Heat a drizzle of olive oil in it over medium-high heat. Shape @ground beef{10%oz} into 2 patties slightly wider than the bread. Season with salt and pepper. Add to pan and cook until just shy of desired doneness, ~{2-4%minutes} per side. Sprinkle @mozzarella cheese{1/2%cup} on top. Cover pan and cook until cheese melts, ~{1%minute} more.

Split @ciabatta bread{2} in half. Toast in toaster oven or oven until golden, ~{3-5%minutes}. Meanwhile, halve @heirloom grape tomatoes{4%oz} lengthwise.

Add @mixed greens{2%oz}, tomatoes, and @dried cranberries{1%oz} to #bowl{} with vinaigrette and toss to combine. Season with salt and pepper.

Fill ciabattas with beef patties, onion, and a few leaves from salad. Divide between plates and serve with remaining salad on the side.

> Burgers are about as all-American as you can get. But that doesn't mean they don't have dreams of voyaging to faraway places. These patties on ciabatta are what happens when cheeseburgers take a trip to Italy. Between the sweetness of the caramelized onion on top, the way the mozzarella melts into loose strands, and the tangy kick brought by balsamic vinegar dressing, you could say these burgers are loaded with dolce vita attitude.